{"key":"processedPost-17736975","value":{"id":17736975,"first":17736027,"last":28126722,"when":1359897516,"utime":"02/03/13 03:18 PM","content":"In the sense of accuracy, using wax paper or bubble wrap, etc., creates a mini-fruiting chamber just above the substrate.&nbsp; It's not a casing.&nbsp; A casing layer does part of this job, but a casing also holds moisture for the flush.<br />I've done many trays in open air with no fruiting chamber just by using wax paper.&nbsp; You can even fold it creatively and use on brf cakes.&nbsp; I like the idea of the irregular surface of bubble wrap, and this is why we wrinkle up the wax paper first.&nbsp; I would worry about the plastic though and its effect on the tops of the fruits as they push it out of the way.&nbsp; Just be careful and lift it often to fan.<br />RR","title":"Re: The official bubble wrap casing"}}